TITLE: Stocks Return to Earth, With the S&P 500 Nearing a Bear Market
SUMMARY: The market has been producing double-digit returns for investors, even at moments of great national strife. But the party has ended and it may be a long time before it begins again.

TITLE: Russian Shipping Traffic Remains Strong as Sanctions Take Time to Bite
SUMMARY: The traffic was robust in March and April, reflecting the time it takes for sanctions to come into effect and an enduring profit motive for trading Russian energy.

TITLE: New Data Show Few Black Economists at the Fed
SUMMARY: The central bank has made few strides in hiring a more racially diverse staff of economics doctorates. Entry-level jobs are a different story.

TITLE: Jerome Powell Confirmed for a Second Term as Fed Chair
SUMMARY: Jerome Powell, whom the Senate confirmed to a second term on Thursday, said allowing rapid inflation to persist would be more painful.

TITLE: Cryptocurrencies Melt Down in a ‘Perfect Storm’ of Fear and Panic
SUMMARY: A steep sell-off that gained momentum this week starkly illustrated the risks of the experimental and unregulated digital currencies.

TITLE: Why Union Efforts at Starbucks Have Spread Further Than at Amazon
SUMMARY: Why has the union campaign spread so much further at the coffee chain than at the e-commerce giant?

TITLE: Senate Confirms Philip Jefferson as a Fed Governor
SUMMARY: Lawmakers have now confirmed three of Mr. Biden’s nominees to the seven-person Fed Board of Governors in Washington.

TITLE: New F.T.C. Majority Gives Lina Khan a Chance to Push an Aggressive Agenda
SUMMARY: The confirmation of a third Democrat creates an opportunity for Lina Khan, the Federal Trade Commission’s chair, to advance efforts to rein in corporate power.

TITLE: Child care benefits could help ease the worker crunch, an advocacy campaign says.
SUMMARY: A survey by McKinsey & Company and Marshall Plan for Moms found that few workers had access to child care benefits, but most mothers said such benefits would make them more likely to accept a job.

TITLE: U.S. Inflation Is Still Climbing Rapidly
SUMMARY: Inflation data showed a slowdown in annual price increases in April, but a closely watched monthly price measure continues to rise at an uncomfortably brisk rate.

TITLE: Fear and Loathing Return to Tech Start-Ups
SUMMARY: Workers are dumping their stock, companies are cutting costs, and layoffs abound as troubling economic forces hit tech start-ups.

TITLE: Fed Confronts Why It May Have Acted Too Slowly on Inflation
SUMMARY: Central bankers have been asking whether they should have reacted faster to rising inflation last year — and are learning from the recent past.

TITLE: Biden Says Inflation Is His ‘Top Domestic Priority’
SUMMARY: Rising prices could hurt President Biden’s party in the midterm elections, and he sought on Tuesday to turn the debate over the economy against his opponents.

TITLE: For Tens of Millions of Americans, the Good Times Are Right Now
SUMMARY: Their houses are piggy banks, their retirement accounts are up and their bosses are eager to please. When the boom ends, everything will change.

TITLE: States Turn to Tax Cuts as Inflation Stays Hot
SUMMARY: Tax reductions and rebates that are being proposed to help people cope could have the unintended effect of pushing prices higher.

TITLE: U.S. to Lift Tariffs on Ukrainian Steel
SUMMARY: The Biden administration will lift a 25 percent tariff on the Ukrainian steel sector for one year to help the country’s economy.

TITLE: Taxpayers May Foot Bill for Penn Station Revitalization, Report Says
SUMMARY: New York State wants to rebuild the transit hub in Midtown Manhattan and pay for the improvements through a larger real estate development.

TITLE: Fed Officials Are on the Defensive as High Inflation Lingers
SUMMARY: Critics have accused the Federal Reserve of not reacting quickly enough to tame rising prices. On Friday, a Fed governor explained why it took so long.

TITLE: NLRB Finds Merit in Union Accusations Against Amazon and Starbucks
SUMMARY: Workers had accused the companies of unlawful behavior during recent union campaigns.

TITLE: Amazon Fires Senior Managers Tied to Unionized Staten Island Warehouse
SUMMARY: Company officials said the terminations were the result of an internal review, while the fired managers saw it as a response to the recent union victory.
